Dataset: FitBit Fitness Tracker Data

Business Task

Bellabeat wants to gain insights from smart device usage trends to improve customer engagement and marketing strategy.

Data Cleaning

# Convert date columns to Date format
daily_activity$ActivityDate <- as.Date(daily_activity$ActivityDate, format="%m/%d/%Y")
sleep_day$SleepDay <- as.Date(sleep_day$SleepDay, format="%m/%d/%Y")

# Remove duplicates and missing values
sleep_day <- sleep_day %>% distinct() %>% drop_na()

# Merge datasets on Id and Date
merged_data <- merge(daily_activity, sleep_day, by.x=c("Id", "ActivityDate"), by.y=c("Id", "SleepDay"), all.x=TRUE)

Visualizing Key Insights

Distribution of Daily Steps

ggplot(merged_data, aes(x = TotalSteps)) + 
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 1000, fill = "blue", alpha = 0.7) + 
  labs(title = "Distribution of Daily Steps", x = "Total Steps", y = "Count") + 
  theme_minimal()

Relationship Between Steps and Sedentary Minutes

ggplot(merged_data, aes(x = TotalSteps, y = SedentaryMinutes)) + 
  geom_point(alpha = 0.5, color = "blue") +  
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", color = "red") +  
  labs(title = "Steps Taken vs. Sedentary Minutes", x = "Total Steps", y = "Sedentary Minutes") +
  theme_minimal()
## `geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'

Sleep vs. Time in Bed

ggplot(merged_data, aes(x = TotalMinutesAsleep, y = TotalTimeInBed)) +
  geom_point(alpha = 0.5, color = "green") +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", color = "red") +
  labs(title = "Sleep Duration vs. Time in Bed", x = "Total Minutes Asleep", y = "Total Time in Bed") +
  theme_minimal()

Segmenting Users by Activity Level

# Categorizing users into activity levels
merged_data <- merged_data %>%
  mutate(ActivityLevel = case_when(
    TotalSteps < 5000 ~ "Low",          # Sedentary
    TotalSteps >= 5000 & TotalSteps < 10000 ~ "Moderate",  # Active
    TotalSteps >= 10000 ~ "High"        # Very Active
  ))

Distribution of Activity Levels

ggplot(merged_data, aes(x = ActivityLevel, fill = ActivityLevel)) +
  geom_bar() +
  labs(title = "User Distribution by Activity Level", x = "Activity Level", y = "Count") +
  theme_minimal()

Steps vs. Sleep Analysis

ggplot(merged_data, aes(x = TotalSteps, y = TotalMinutesAsleep, color = ActivityLevel)) +
  geom_point(alpha = 0.5) +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", color = "black") +
  labs(title = "Relationship Between Steps and Sleep", x = "Total Steps", y = "Total Minutes Asleep") +
  theme_minimal()

Activity Trends by Day of the Week

# Extract day of the week
merged_data$DayOfWeek <- weekdays(merged_data$ActivityDate)
ggplot(merged_data, aes(x = DayOfWeek, y = TotalSteps, fill = DayOfWeek)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  labs(title = "Activity Trends by Day of the Week", x = "Day of the Week", y = "Total Steps") +
  theme_minimal()

Insights & Recommendations

  • Users with higher step counts tend to be more active and burn more calories.
  • There is a strong correlation between sleep duration and time in bed, but some users may have poor sleep efficiency.
  • Sedentary behavior remains high, even for active users, indicating a need for targeted movement reminders.
  • Encourage Low & Moderate Activity Users → Position Bellabeat as an entry-level fitness tracker to help users gradually increase their steps.
  • Support High Activity Users → Market advanced analytics to users already taking 10,000+ steps.
  • Leverage Sedentary Trends → Introduce features like “Active Hour Alerts” to encourage users to move more.
  • Promote Sleep & Recovery Features → Market Bellabeat as a wellness tool, not just a fitness tracker.
  • Weekend vs. Weekday Activity Campaigns → Adjust marketing messages based on activity patterns.

🚀 Next Steps:
- Further investigate user segments (e.g., group users into “low, moderate, high activity”)
- Explore seasonal trends in fitness tracker usage
- Develop business recommendations for Bellabeat based on deeper insights
